{"title_page": "Turtle Island Light", "text_new": "{{Infobox lighthouse\n| name = Turtle Island Light\n| image_name = \n| caption = \n| location = Turtle Island ([[Lake Erie]])\n| yearbuilt = 1831<br/>1866 (current tower)\n| yearlit =\n| automated = No\n| yeardeactivated = 1904\n| foundation =\n| construction = [[Brick]]\n| shape = Square\n| marking =\n| height = {{convert|44|ft}}\n| focalheight =\n| lens =\n| currentlens = removed\n| intensity =\n| range = {{convert|14|mi|nmi km|disp=flip}}\n| characteristic =\n| fogsignal =\n| racon =\n| admiralty =\n| canada =\n| NGA =\n| ARLHS = USA-859<ref>{{cite web|last=[[Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society]]|url=http://wlol.arlhs.com/lighthouse/USA859.html|year=2010|title=Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society, Turtle Island (Lake Erie) Light, ARLHS USA-859|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=[[Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society]]|url=http://wlol.arlhs.com/index.php?mode=alpha&letter=T|year=2010|title=Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society, World List of Lights (WLOL)|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref>\n| USCG =\n}}\nWhen [[Turtle Island (Lake Erie)|Turtle Island]] fell back to federal ownership, the newly established Port of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] received $5,000 of federal funding from [[United States Congress|Congress]] to build the '''Turtle Island Lighthouse''' in 1831.<ref name=FRIENDS>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Kraig|url=http://www.lighthousefriends.com/light.asp?ID=271|year=2010|title=Turtle Island, Ohio|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref> At the time, the island's area was approximately {{convert|6.67|acre}}, and the island included the lighthouse, the [[lighthouse keeper]]'s residence, and a small farm.<ref name=CAPTAIN/>\n\nUnlike most islands in Lake Erie, Turtle Island consists primarily of clay and gravel deposits and was subjected to constant erosion, which is why some believed it to not be a real island.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}  By 1839, lake storms and waves reduced the island by approximately 77% down to an area of only {{convert|1.5|acre}}.  Congress spent tens of thousands of dollars to no avail to prevent the erosion of the island.  In 1866, an updated lighthouse costing $12,000 was constructed.  It was described as one of the finest lighthouses on the Great Lakes, and its light could be seen up to {{convert|14|mi}} away.<ref name=FRIENDS/>  However, the erosion of the island continued to threaten the lighthouse to the point where a {{convert|4|ft|adj=on}} tall concrete wall was constructed in 1883 around the lighthouse to prevent crashing waves and erosion from damaging the structure.<ref name=CAPTAIN/>  Constant lake storms bombarded the tiny island.  When the nearby [[Toledo Harbor Light]] was completed in 1904, the Turtle Island Lighthouse was no longer needed and was decommissioned after having cost the United States an untold amount of money to continuously maintain over the past 72 years.  During those 72 years, there were no shipwrecks within the vicinity of Turtle Island.<ref name=CAPTAIN>{{cite web |last=Archinger |first=Warren |url=http://www.captain-johns.com/Ohio/Turtle.html|year=2004 |title=Ohio Lighthouses - Turtle Island Light, Maumee Bay - Lake Erie|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere were two keepers of the lighthouse: Ann Edson (1869\u20131870) and William Haynes (1875\u20131904).<ref name=\"Depot\">{{cite web|last=Lighthouse Depot |url=http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286 |year=2010 |title=Turtle Island Light |access-date=March 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103104226/http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286 |archive-date=January 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gardner, B. Ellen. ''Turtle Island Lighthouse: The Darkened Light''.  Cornwall, New York: Hawk's Cry Publications, 1997. {{ISBN|0-9649679-2-8}}\n* Oleszewski, Wes. ''Great Lakes Lighthouses, American and Canadian: A Comprehensive Directory/Guide to Great Lakes Lighthouses''. Gwinn, Michigan: Avery Color Studios, Inc., 1998. {{ISBN|0-932212-98-0}}.\n* Turtle Island Light Station, The Keepers' Log, ''Notice to Keepers'' Volume 10, Issue 4, Page 40.\n* [[United States Coast Guard|U.S. Coast Guard]]. ''Historically Famous Lighthouses''. Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1957.\n* Wright, Larry and Wright, Patricia. ''Great Lakes Lighthouses Encyclopedia''. Erin, Ontario: Boston Mills Press, 2006. {{ISBN|1-55046-399-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lighthousefriends.com/light.asp?ID=271 Turtle Island Lighthouse at Lighthouse Friends]\n*[http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286&bhcd2=1250169644 Lighthouse Depot: Turtle Island.]\n\n{{Lighthouses of Michigan}}\n{{Lighthouses of Ohio}}\n\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1831]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1866]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lucas County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1831 establishments in Michigan Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lighthouse\n| name = Turtle Island Light\n| image_name = \n| caption = \n| location = Turtle Island ([[Lake Erie]])\n| yearbuilt = 1831<br/>1866 (current tower)\n| yearlit =\n| automated = No\n| yeardeactivated = 1904\n| foundation =\n| construction = [[Brick]]\n| shape = Square\n| marking =\n| height = {{convert|44|ft}}\n| focalheight =\n| lens =\n| currentlens = removed\n| intensity =\n| range = {{convert|14|mi|nmi km|disp=flip}}\n| characteristic =\n| fogsignal =\n| racon =\n| admiralty =\n| canada =\n| NGA =\n| ARLHS = USA-859<ref>{{cite web|last=[[Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society]]|url=http://wlol.arlhs.com/lighthouse/USA859.html|year=2010|title=Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society, Turtle Island (Lake Erie) Light, ARLHS USA-859|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=[[Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society]]|url=http://wlol.arlhs.com/index.php?mode=alpha&letter=T|year=2010|title=Amateur Radio Lighthouse Society, World List of Lights (WLOL)|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref>\n| USCG =\n}}\nWhen [[Turtle Island (Lake Erie)|Turtle Island]] fell back to federal ownership, the newly established Port of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] received $5,000 of federal funding from [[United States Congress|Congress]] to build the '''Turtle Island Lighthouse''' in 1831.<ref name=FRIENDS>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Kraig|url=http://www.lighthousefriends.com/light.asp?ID=271|year=2010|title=Turtle Island, Ohio|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref> At the time, the island's area was approximately {{convert|6.67|acre}}, and the island included the lighthouse, the [[lighthouse keeper]]'s residence, and a small farm.<ref name=CAPTAIN/>\n\nUnlike most islands in Lake Erie, Turtle Island consists primarily of clay and gravel deposits and was subjected to constant erosion, which is why some believed it to not be a real island.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}  By 1839, lake storms and waves reduced the island by approximately 77% down to an area of only {{convert|1.5|acre}}.  Congress spent tens of thousands of dollars to no avail to prevent the erosion of the island.  In 1866, an updated lighthouse costing $12,000 was constructed.  It was described as one of the finest lighthouses on the Great Lakes, and its light could be seen up to {{convert|14|mi}} away.<ref name=FRIENDS/>  However, the erosion of the island continued to threaten the lighthouse to the point where a {{convert|4|ft|adj=on}} tall concrete wall was constructed in 1883 around the lighthouse to prevent crashing waves and erosion from damaging the structure.<ref name=CAPTAIN/>  Constant lake storms bombarded the tiny island.  When the nearby [[Toledo Harbor Light]] was completed in 1904, the Turtle Island Lighthouse was no longer needed and was decommissioned after having cost the United States an untold amount of money to continuously maintain over the past 72 years.  During those 72 years, there were no shipwrecks within the vicinity of Turtle Island.<ref name=CAPTAIN>{{cite web |last=Archinger |first=Warren |url=http://www.captain-johns.com/Ohio/Turtle.html|year=2004 |title=Ohio Lighthouses - Turtle Island Light, Maumee Bay - Lake Erie|accessdate=March 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThere were two keepers of the lighthouse: Ann Edson (1869\u20131870) and William Haynes (1875\u20131904).<ref name=\"Depot\">{{cite web|last=Lighthouse Depot |url=http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286 |year=2010 |title=Turtle Island Light |access-date=March 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103104226/http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286 |archive-date=January 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gardner, B. Ellen. ''Turtle Island Lighthouse: The Darkened Light''.  Cornwall, New York: Hawk's Cry Publications, 1997. {{ISBN|0-9649679-2-8}}\n* Oleszewski, Wes. ''Great Lakes Lighthouses, American and Canadian: A Comprehensive Directory/Guide to Great Lakes Lighthouses''. Gwinn, Michigan: Avery Color Studios, Inc., 1998. {{ISBN|0-932212-98-0}}.\n* Turtle Island Light Station, The Keepers' Log, ''Notice to Keepers'' Volume 10, Issue 4, Page 40.\n* [[United States Coast Guard|U.S. Coast Guard]]. ''Historically Famous Lighthouses''. Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1957.\n* Wright, Larry and Wright, Patricia. ''Great Lakes Lighthouses Encyclopedia''. Erin, Ontario: Boston Mills Press, 2006. {{ISBN|1-55046-399-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lighthousefriends.com/light.asp?ID=271 Turtle Island Lighthouse at Lighthouse Friends]\n*[http://www.lighthousedepot.com/lite_explorer.asp?action=display_details&LighthouseID=286&bhcd2=1250169644 Lighthouse Depot: Turtle Island.]\n\n{{Lighthouses of Michigan}}\n{{Lighthouses of Ohio}}\n\n