thly Review]]'', Volume 66, Number 9. Book review of Walter Johnson, ''River of Dark Dreams: Slavery and Empire in the Cotton Kingdom'' (Cambridge, MA: Belknap Press, 2013)\n* Electronic Code of Federal Regulations (e-CFR), Title 50: Wildlife and Fisheries Part 22-Eagle permits {{cite web|url=http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&tpl=/ecfrbrowse/Title50/50cfr22_main_02.tpl |title=Electronic Code of Federal Regulations |publisher=Ecfr.gpoaccess.gov |date=February 27, 2007 |accessdate=August 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610034613/http://ecfr.gpoaccess.gov/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=ecfr&tpl=%2Fecfrbrowse%2FTitle50%2F50cfr22_main_02.tpl |archivedate=June 10, 2007 |df= }}\n* Hirschfelder, Arlene B.; Byler, Mary G.; & Dorris, Michael. ''Guide to research on North American Indians''. American Library Association (1983). {{ISBN|0-8389-0353-3}}.\n* Jones, Peter N. ''Respect for the Ancestors: American Indian Cultural Affiliation in the American West''. Boulder, CO: Bauu Press (2005). {{ISBN|0-9721349-2-1}}.\n* {{cite book|last1=Kroeber |first1= Alfred L. |title= Cultural and Natural Areas of Native North America |publisher=University of California Publications in American Archaeology and Ethnology|year=1939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_M70pNlgDf0C}}\n* Nichols, Roger L. ''Indians in the United States & Canada, A Comparative History''. University of Nebraska Press (1998). {{ISBN|0-8032-8377-6}}.\n* {{cite book |last1=Pohl |first1=Frances K. |url=https://archive.org/details/framingamericaso0000pohl/page/54 |title=Framing America: A Social History of American Art |location=New York |publisher=Thames & Hudson |year=2002 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/framingamericaso0000pohl/page/54 54\u201356, 105\u2013106 & 110\u2013111] |isbn=978-0-500-23792-2 }}\n* {{cite journal|last1 = Shanley|first1 = Kathryn Winona|url = https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=76961328|title = The Indians America Loves to Love and Read: American Indian Identity and Cultural Appropriation|journal = American Indian Quarterly|volume = 21|issue = 4|year = 1997|pages = 675\u2013702|doi = 10.2307/1185719|jstor = 1185719|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110315021530/http://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=76961328|archivedate = March 15, 2011|df = }}\n* {{cite journal|last1 = Shanley|first1 = Kathryn Winona|year = 2004|title = The Paradox of Native American Indian Intellectualism and Literature|url = https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&se=gglsc&d=5008600865|journal = Melus|volume = 29|issue =3/4|pages = 273\u2013292|doi = 10.2307/4141855|jstor = 4141855}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Shohat |first1= Ella |last2= Stam |first2= Robert|title= Unthinking Eurocentrism: Multiculturalism and the Media |location= New York |publisher=Routledge |year= 1994|isbn=978-0-415-06324-1}}\n* Sletcher, Michael, \"North American Indians\", in Will Kaufman and Heidi Macpherson, eds., ''Britain and the Americas: Culture, Politics, and History'', New York: Oxford University Press, 2005, 2 vols.\n* {{cite book|last1=Snipp |first1= C.M. |title=American Indians: The first of this land|location = New York |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year= 1989|url=https://archive.org/details/americanindiansf00sniprich|url-access=registration |isbn=978-0-87154-822-1}}\n* Sturtevant, William C. (Ed.). ''[[Handbook of North American Indians]]'' (Vol. 1\u201320). Washington, D. C.: Smithsonian Institution. (Vols. 1\u20133, 16, 18\u201320 not yet published), (1978\u2013present).\n* Tiller, Veronica E. (Ed.). ''Discover Indian Reservations USA: A Visitors' Welcome Guide''. Foreword by [[Ben Nighthorse Campbell]]. Denver, CO: Council Publications, 1992. {{ISBN|0-9632580-0-1}}.\n* Washburn, Wilcomb E. ''The Indian in America'' (1975)\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Commons category|Native Americans in the United States}}\n* [http://www.bia.gov/ Official website] of the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]], part of the [[U.S. Department of the Interior]]\n* [http://www.ncai.org/ Official website] of the [[National Congress of American Indians]]\n* [https://www.archives.gov/research/native-americans American Indian Records] from the [[National Archives and Records Administration]]\n* [http://www.nmai.si.edu/ Official website] of the [[National Museum of the American Indian]], part of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n* [http://www.narf.org/nill/index.html National Indian Law Library] of the [[Native American Rights Fund]] \u2013 a law library of federal Indian and tribal law\n\n{{Demographics of the United States}}\n{{Indigenous peoples of the Americas}}\n{{Native American rights}}\n{{Cultural areas of indigenous North Americans}}\n{{Indigenous peoples by continent}}\n{{Native American topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples in the United States|*]]\n[[Category:Native American history| ]]\n[[Category:Native American topics| ]]\n[[Category:American culture]]\n[[Category:History of civil rights in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Social history of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:1edf:e000:a97e:a607:5688:7203", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Umuokpara", "text_new": "'''Umuopara''' are a [[clan]] of the [[Igbo people]] of [[Umuahia]] [[Nigeria]]. The Umuopara reside in seven villages known as ''umunne asaa'' namely: [[Ezeleke]], [[Ogbodiukwu]], Ekenobizi, Ehume, Ogbodinibe, Umuihi and Umunwawa. \n\n==Culture==\n\nUmuopara is generally regarded as the cradle of Umuahia civilization. In the past it was known for the [[Egwu festival]] which was celebrated at Omaegwu. Umuopara is presently known for the [[Ekpe festival]] which is also celebrated by other clans in Umuahia, notably Ibeku and Ohuhu. The first ever Ekpe festival took place in [[Ogbodiukwu Umuopara]]. The new ''Yam festival'' is also celebrated in Umuopara. The supreme deity in Umuopara during pre-colonial times was the Ojam. Most of the people in modern-day Umuopara are Christians with Methodist and Anglican as the dominant denominations.\n\nSome notable members of Umuopara include the Late Honorable Apugo Onyekwere, first University graduate in Umuopara, Late Dr. Chief Chikezie Sylvester Ugorji who spearheaded the project that brought water and electricity to Ehume Village, Late Chief B.O.N Eluwa, Chief Steve Ihedigbo, Chief G.N.A Atulomah, Chief Levi Nwokeafor, Pharm U.N.O uwaga, Late S.B.A Atulomah, Akpunku Iheuwa, Chuks Nwononiwu, Chief Anab Atulomah,Chief Chibiko Ukanwoke, C.S.L Nwosu, Chief Odigbo, His Hon. Ephraim Atulomah, Chikeziri Onyekwere, Chief Ineama, Okey Ezeala, Late [[Eze]] J.N Amaechi, Hon Acho Obioma,Engr Onu Eluwa,Okechukwu Olekibe, Chima Onyekwere,AIG Uzor Amakaulo Rtd, S.I (Acho) Onukaogu,Late Prof Paul Ogbuehi,Enyinnaya Odigbo,Hon Ndukwe Adindu,Rear Admiral Aham Eluwa,Chidozie John Ezeoma and many others.\n\n==Origin==\n\nThere are several beliefs regarding the origin of Umuopara people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gounesco.com/the-festivals-of-nigeria/|title=The festivals of Nigeria|last=January 17|first=Lorana|last2=2018|date=2018-01-17|website=GoUNESCO - Make Heritage Fun!|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> One view is that the Umuopara people did not migrate from anywhere.  While this view sounds plausible, some villages in Umuopara today can convincingly trace their old settlement to places outside Umuopara.\n\nIt has been suggested that at least sections of the people of Umuopara came from obowu and mbaise areas.\n\nAccording to oral traditions Eku was the ancestor of the people of Umuopara. Eku had two sons namely Opara who became the founder of Umuopara and Ibe who founded Ibeku. Omaegwu in Umuopara was his first point of settlement. Opara being the first son remained while Ibe moved east to present day Ibeku land. Nkwoegwu in present-day Ohuhu clan was a meeting point for the two brothers during the annual egwu festival. This was before the later migrations from Obowu area by the Ohuhu people. Some sons of Ibe later moved further east to establish Abam, Ohafia and Edda.\n\n==References==\n*http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/613946/Umuahia\n*http://www.myinfobell.com/city_ng_umuahia.html\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ohuhu.com/ -The Community Website]\n\n{{Igbo topics}}\n\n[[Category:Igbo clans]]\n[[Category:Igbo subgroups]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-ethno-group-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Umuopara''' are a [[clan]] of the [[Igbo people]] of [[Umuahia]] [[Nigeria]]. The Umuopara reside in seven villages known as ''umunne asaa'' namely: [[Ezeleke]], Ogbodiukwu, Ekenobizi, Ehume, Ogbodinibe, Umuihi and Umunwawa. \n\n==Culture==\n\nUmuopara is generally regarded as the cradle of Umuahia civilization. In the past it was known for the [[Egwu festival]] which was celebrated at Omaegwu. Umuopara is presently known for the [[Ekpe festival]] which is also celebrated by other clans in Umuahia, notably Ibeku and Ohuhu. The first ever Ekpe festival took place in [[Ogbodiukwu Umuopara]]. The new ''Yam festival'' is also celebrated in Umuopara. The supreme deity in Umuopara during pre-colonial times was the Ojam. Most of the people in modern-day Umuopara are Christians with Methodist and Anglican as the dominant denominations.\n\nSome notable members of Umuopara include the Late Honorable Apugo Onyekwere, first University graduate in Umuopara, Late Dr. Chief Chikezie Sylvester Ugorji who spearheaded the project that brought water and electricity to Ehume Village, Late Chief B.O.N Eluwa, Chief Steve Ihedigbo, Chief G.N.A Atulomah, Chief Levi Nwokeafor, Pharm U.N.O uwaga, Late S.B.A Atulomah, Akpunku Iheuwa, Chuks Nwononiwu, Chief Anab Atulomah,Chief Chibiko Ukanwoke, C.S.L Nwosu, Chief Odigbo, His Hon. Ephraim Atulomah, Chikeziri Onyekwere, Chief Ineama, Okey Ezeala, Late [[Eze]] J.N Amaechi, Hon Acho Obioma,Engr Onu Eluwa,Okechukwu Olekibe, Chima Onyekwere,AIG Uzor Amakaulo Rtd, S.I (Acho) Onukaogu,Late Prof Paul Ogbuehi,Enyinnaya Odigbo,Hon Ndukwe Adindu,Rear Admiral Aham Eluwa,Chidozie John Ezeoma and many others.\n\n==Origin==\n\nThere are several beliefs regarding the origin of Umuopara people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gounesco.com/the-festivals-of-nigeria/|title=The festivals of Nigeria|last=January 17|first=Lorana|last2=2018|date=2018-01-17|website=GoUNESCO - Make Heritage Fun!|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> One view is that the Umuopara people did not migrate from anywhere.  While this view sounds plausible, some villages in Umuopara today can convincingly trace their old settlement to places outside Umuopara.\n\nIt has been suggested that at least sections of the people of Umuopara came from obowu and mbaise areas.\n\nAccording to oral traditions Eku was the ancestor of the people of Umuopara. Eku had two sons namely Opara who became the founder of Umuopara and Ibe who founded Ibeku. Omaegwu in Umuopara was his first point of settlement. Opara being the first son remained while Ibe moved east to present day Ibeku land. Nkwoegwu in present-day Ohuhu clan was a meeting point for the two brothers during the annual egwu festival. This was before the later migrations from Obowu area by the Ohuhu people. Some sons of Ibe later moved further east to establish Abam, Ohafia and Edda.\n\n==References==\n*http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/613946/Umuahia\n*http://www.myinfobell.com/city_ng_umuahia.html\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ohuhu.com/ -The Community Website]\n\n{{Igbo topics}}\n\n[[Category:Igbo clans]]\n[[Category:Igbo subgroups]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-ethno-group-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pratat", "label": "safe", "comment": "linked another village", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umuokpara"}
{"title_page": "Leon Mettam", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Leon Mettam\n| image = Mettam, Leon.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| fullname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|12|09|df=y}}<ref name=\"Lincoln City Football Squads\">{{cite web|title=Lincoln City Football Squads|url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/2006-2007/fltwo/lincoln.htm|work=Football Squads|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], England<ref name=\"Lincoln City Football Squads\"/>\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"Lincoln City Football Squads\"/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]]\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132005 | youthclubs1 = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| years1 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs1 = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| caps1 =  5 | goals1 =  7\n| years2 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs2 = [[Stamford A.F.C.|Stamford]]\n| caps2 =    | goals2 =  \n| years3 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs3 = [[Corby Town F.C.|Corby Town]]\n| caps3 = 35 | goals3 = 23\n| years4 = 2010\u20132012 | clubs4 = [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]]\n| caps4 =    | goals4 =  \n| years5 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs5 = [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]]\n| caps5 = 80 | goals5 = 66\n| years6 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs6 = [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]]\n| caps6 =  18 | goals6 =  5\n| years7 = 2015      | clubs7 = \u2192 [[King's Lynn Town F.C.|King's Lynn Town]] (loan)\n| caps7 =  5 | goals7 =  3\n| years8 = 2016\u20132017     | clubs8 = [[King's Lynn Town F.C.|King's Lynn Town]]\n| caps8 = 19    | goals8 =  5\n| years9 = 2017\u20132018    | clubs9 = \u2192 [[Spalding United F.C.|Spalding United]] (loan)\n| caps9 =    | goals9 =  \n| years10 = 2019  | clubs10 = \n [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]]\n|caps10 = 0    | goals10 = 0\n|years11 = 0    |goals11 = 0\n(UTC)\n}}\n'''Leon Mettam''' (born 9 December 1986) is a former English [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] for [[Northern Counties East League]] club [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]]<ref name=\"Leon Mettam\">{{cite web|title=Leon Mettam|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=43083|work=soccerbase.com|accessdate=1 November 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.spaldingtoday.co.uk/sport/football/non-league/football-spalding-united-add-striker-leon-mettam-in-loan-deal-1-7789802 FOOTBALL: Spalding United add striker Leon Mettam in loan deal]\u201a spaldingtoday.co.uk, 25 January 2017</ref> He played in [[the Football League]] for [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]. Well known for his tweet runners run players player due to him being strange. Acts like he was a top level pro for years but really only played 5 games for Lincoln\n\n==Playing career==\n===Gainsborough Trinity===\nIn July 2010, Mettam left The Steelmen to join league rivals [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gainsborough striker Leon Mettam reveals despair following release by Lincoln |url=http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Gainsborough-striker-Mettam-reveals-depths-despair-following-release-Lincoln/story-11204260-detail/story.html |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=5 July 2010 |website= |publisher=LincolnshireEcho.co.uk |accessdate=5 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Worksop Town===\nMettam then went on to join ambitious [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]], who were managed by his former [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] youth team coach, [[Simon Clark (English footballer)|Simon Clark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Leon Mettam joins ambitious Worksop Town |url=http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Leon-Mettam-joins-ambitious-Worksop-Town/story-16184931-detail/story.html |last1=Curtis |first1=Leigh |last2= |first2= |date=25 May 2012 |website= |publisher=LincolnshireEcho.co.uk |accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tamworth===\nOn 10 June 2014, Mettam, and his [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]] teammate [[Shane Clarke]] joined [[Conference North]] side [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]].\nFollowing an ankle injury in October 2014 which kept him sidelined for the remainder of the year, Mettam joined Northern Premier League side [[King's Lynn Town F.C.|King's Lynn Town]] on a month's loan in January 2015, scoring three times in five appearances.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tamworthherald.co.uk/Tamworth-swoop-Mettam-Clarke/story-21212471-detail/story.html |title=Tamworth swoop for Mettam and Clarke |last1=Panter |first1=Matt |last2= |first2= |date=10 June 2014 |website= |publisher=TamworthHerald.co.uk |accessdate=10 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714112106/http://www.tamworthherald.co.uk/Tamworth-swoop-Mettam-Clarke/story-21212471-detail/story.html |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===King's Lynn Town===\nAfter being released by Tamworth at the end of the 2015/16 season; Mettam was unveiled to King's Lynn Town's supporters at a pre-season fans' forum on 7 June 2016 on a two-year contract.<ref>http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/king_s_lynn_town_add_even_more_firepower_to_their_ranks_by_signing_goal_machine_leon_mettam_1_4567772</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 22 May 2014.}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=43083 |title=Leon Mettam Stats |work=Soccerbase}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref group=Note>Includes other competitive competitions, including the [[Football League Trophy]] & [[FA Trophy]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" valign=\"center\"|[[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n|[[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Footba