5|date=28 May 2000|publisher=Chebucto.ns.ca|accessdate=27 June 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[22nd G7 summit|22nd]] || 27\u201329 June 1996 || {{Country|France}} ||[[Jacques Chirac]] || [[Lyon]], [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] ||[[International organization]]s' debut to G7 Summits periodically. The invited ones here were: United Nations, [[World Bank Group|World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund]] and the [[World Trade Organization]].<ref name=\"G8 paper\">Kirton, John. [http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/scholar/kirton-performance-080717.pdf \"A Summit of Substantial Success: The Performance of the 2008 G8\"; pp. 88, 89] ''G8 Information Centre&nbsp;\u2013 University of Toronto'' 17 July 2008.</ref>|| \n|\n|-\n| [[23rd G8 summit|23rd]] || 20\u201322 June 1997|| {{Country|United States}} ||[[Bill Clinton]] ||[[Denver]], [[Colorado]] || Russia joins the group, forming G8||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://1997-2001.state.gov/www/issues/economic/summit/g8.html|title=Denver Summit of the Eight|publisher=State.gov|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[24th G8 summit|24th]] || 15\u201317 May 1998 || {{Country|United Kingdom}} ||[[Tony Blair]] || [[Birmingham]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]|| ||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://birmingham.g8summit.gov.uk/|title=1998: Britain Welcomes the Summit of World Leaders|date=12 December 1998|publisher=United Kingdom. gov.uk|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981212012854/http://birmingham.g8summit.gov.uk/|archivedate=12 December 1998|accessdate=21 May 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[25th G8 summit|25th]] || 18\u201320 June 1999 || {{Country|Germany}} ||[[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]|| [[Cologne]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] ||First Summit of the [[G-20 major economies]] at [[Berlin]]||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sipri.org/contents/expcon/1999summit.html|title=1999 G8 summit documents|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050226154039/http://www.sipri.org/contents/expcon/1999summit.html|archivedate=26 February 2005|accessdate=27 June 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[26th G8 summit|26th]] || 21\u201323 July 2000 || {{Country|Japan}} ||[[Yoshir\u014d Mori]] ||[[Nago, Okinawa]] || Formation of the [[G8+5]] starts, when South Africa was invited. Until the [[38th G8 summit]] in 2012, it has been invited to the Summit annually without interruption. Also, with permission from a G8 leader, other nations were invited to the Summit on a periodical basis for the first time. Nigeria, Algeria and Senegal accepted their invitations here. The [[World Health Organization]] was also invited for the first time.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" />||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/policy/economy/summit/2000/|title=Kyushu-Okinawa Summit|publisher=MOFA|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[27th G8 summit|27th]] || 21\u201322 July 2001 || {{Country|Italy}} ||[[Silvio Berlusconi]] || [[Genoa]], [[Liguria]] || Leaders from Bangladesh, Mali and El Salvador accepted their invitations here.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" /> Demonstrator [[Carlo Giuliani]] is shot and killed by the [[Carabinieri]] during a violent demonstration. One of the largest and most violent [[anti-globalization movement]] protests occurred for the [[27th G8 summit]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7506609.stm Italy officials convicted over G8], BBC News, 15 July 2008</ref> Following those events and the [[September 11 attacks]] two months later in 2001, the G8 have met at more remote locations.||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8italia.it/index.html|title=Vertice di Genova 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010806171931/http://www.g8italia.it/index.html|archivedate=6 August 2001|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[28th G8 summit|28th]] || 26\u201327 June 2002 || {{Country|Canada}} ||[[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] || [[Kananaskis Improvement District|Kananaskis]], [[Alberta]] || Russia gains permission to officially host a [[32nd G8 summit|G8 Summit]].||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/summit/2002kananaskis/|title=UT G8 Info. Centre. Kananaskis Summit 2002. Summit Contents|publisher=G8.utoronto.ca|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[29th G8 summit|29th]] || 1\u20133 June 2003 || {{Country|France}} ||[[Jacques Chirac]] || [[\u00c9vian-les-Bains]], [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] || The G8+5 was ''unofficially'' made, when China, India, Brazil, and Mexico were invited to this Summit for the first time. South Africa has joined the G8 Summit, since 2000, until the 2012 edition. Other first-time nations that were invited by the French president included: Egypt, Morocco, Saudi Arabia, Malaysia and Switzerland.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" />|| \n|\n|-\n| [[30th G8 summit|30th]] || 8\u201310 June 2004 || {{Country|United States}} ||[[George W. Bush]] || [[Sea Island, Georgia]] || A record number of leaders from 12 different nations accepted their invitations here. Amongst a couple of veteran nations, the others were: Ghana, Afghanistan, Bahrain, Iraq, Jordan, Turkey, Yemen and Uganda.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" /> Also, the [[Death and state funeral of Ronald Reagan|state funeral of former President Ronald Reagan]] took place in Washington during the summit. All of G8 participants attended this funeral, along with 20 more heads of state.||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/g8/2004/|title=Sea Island Summit 2004|publisher=Georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[31st G8 summit|31st]] || 6\u20138 July 2005 || {{Country|United Kingdom}} ||[[Tony Blair]] || [[Gleneagles, Scotland]]|| The G8+5 was officially formed. On the second day of the meeting, [[7 July 2005 London bombings|suicide bombers killed 52 people on the London Underground and a bus]]. Nations that were invited for the first time were Ethiopia and Tanzania. The [[African Union]] and the [[International Energy Agency]] made their debut here.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" /> During the [[31st G8 summit]] in United Kingdom, 225,000 people took to the streets of Edinburgh as part of the [[Make Poverty History]] campaign calling for Trade Justice, Debt Relief and Better Aid. Numerous other demonstrations also took place challenging the legitimacy of the G8.<ref>David Miller [http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/6279 \"Spinning the G8\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528184428/http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/6279 |date=28 May 2009 }}, Zednet, 13 May 2005.</ref>||\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/uk/2005/g8_gleneagles/default.stm|title=Special Reports &#124; G8_Gleneagles|date=17 September 2008|accessdate=8 February 2010|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[32nd G8 summit|32nd]] || 15\u201317 July 2006 || {{Country |Russia}} (only [[G8]] member, not G7)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> ||[[Vladimir Putin]] ||[[Strelna]], [[Saint Petersburg]] || First G8 Summit on Russian Federation soil. Also, the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] and [[UNESCO]] made their debut here.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" />|| \n|\n|-\n| [[33rd G8 summit|33rd]] || 6\u20138 June 2007 || {{Country|Germany}} || [[Angela Merkel]] || [[Heiligendamm]], [[Mecklenburg-Vorpommern]] || Seven different international organizations accepted their invitations to this Summit. The [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] made their debut here.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" />|| \n|\n|-\n| [[34th G8 summit|34th]] || 7\u20139 July 2008 || {{Country|Japan}} || [[Yasuo Fukuda]] ||[[T\u014dyako, Hokkaid\u014d]] || Nations that accepted their G8 Summit invitations for the first time are: Australia, Indonesia and South Korea.<ref name=\"G8 paper\" />||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/policy/economy/summit/2008/index.html|title=Hokkaido Toyako Summit \u2013 TOP|publisher=Mofa.go.jp|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[35th G8 summit|35th]] || 8\u201310 July 2009 || {{Country|Italy}} || [[Silvio Berlusconi]] || [[La Maddalena]], [[Sardinia]] (cancelled)<br /> [[L'Aquila]], [[Abruzzo]] (re-located)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://runninginheels.com/articles/berlusconi-proposes-relocation-of-g8-summit-to-laquila/ |title=Berlusconi Proposes Relocation of G8 Summit to L'Aquila |publisher=Running in heels |date=24 April 2009 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808230903/http://runninginheels.com/articles/berlusconi-proposes-relocation-of-g8-summit-to-laquila/ |archive-date=8 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> || This G8 Summit was originally planned to be in [[La Maddalena]] ([[Sardinia]]), but was moved to L'Aquila as a way of showing Prime Minister Berlusconi's desire to help the region after the [[2009 L'Aquila earthquake]]. Nations that accepted their invitations for the first time were: Angola, Denmark, Netherlands and Spain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.g8italia2009.it/G8/Home/Summit/Partecipanti/G8-G8_Layout_locale-1199882116809_AltriPaesi.htm |title=G8 Summit 2009 \u2013 official website \u2013 Other Countries |publisher=G8italia2009.it |accessdate=8 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406013349/http://www.g8italia2009.it/G8/Home/Summit/Partecipanti/G8-G8_Layout_locale-1199882116809_AltriPaesi.htm |archivedate=6 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A record of ten international organizations were represented in this G8 Summit. For the first time, the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]], the [[International Fund for Agricultural Development]], the [[World Food Programme]], and the [[International Labour Organization]] accepted their invitations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.g8italia2009.it/G8/Home/Summit/Partecipanti/G8-G8_Layout_locale-1199882116809_OrganizzazioniInternazionali.htm |title=G8 Summit 2009 \u2013 official website \u2013 International Organizations |publisher=G8italia2009.it |accessdate=8 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406013354/http://www.g8italia2009.it/G8/Home/Summit/Partecipanti/G8-G8_Layout_locale-1199882116809_OrganizzazioniInternazionali.htm |archive-date=6 April 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8italia2009.it/|title=G8 Online Survey Results|publisher=Summit 2009: G8 From La Maddalena to L'Aquila. g8italia2009.it|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826113834/http://www.g8italia2009.it/|archive-date=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[36th G8 summit|36th]] || 25\u201326 June 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/evaluations/2010muskoka/2010plans/2010-g8plans-100623.pdf |title=Canada's G8 Plans  |accessdate=27 June 2010}}</ref> || {{Country|Canada}} || [[Stephen Harper]] || [[Huntsville, Ontario]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2155 |title=Prime Minister of Canada: Prime Minister announces Canada to host 2010 G8 Summit in Huntsville |publisher=Pm.gc.ca |accessdate=8 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208043545/http://www.pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2155 |archivedate=8 February 2010 |df= }}</ref> || Malawi, Colombia, Haiti, and Jamaica accepted their invitations for the first time.<ref>[http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/summit/2010muskoka/delegations.html Participants at the 2010 Muskoka Summit]. G8 Information Centre. Retrieved 29 June 2010.</ref>||\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g8/summit-sommet/2010/index.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=88|title=2010 Muskoka Summit|publisher=Canadainternational.gc.ca|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410034357/http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/g8/summit-sommet/2010/index.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=88|archivedate=10 April 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=21 May 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[37th G8 summit|37th]] || 26\u201327 May 2011 || {{Country|France}} || [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] || [[Deauville]],<ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/societe/le-prochain-g20-aura-lieu-a-cannes-12-11-2010-1261419_23.php \"Le prochain G20 aura lieu \u00e0 Cannes,\"] ''Le point.'' 12 November 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.g20-g8.com/g8-g20/g8/english/the-2011-summit/host-city/the-city-of-deauville/the-city-of-deauville.739.html The City of Deauville] ''Official 2011 G8 website.'' Retrieved 7 February 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319170128/http://www.g20-g8.com/g8-g20/g8/english/the-2011-summit/host-city/the-city-of-deauville/the-city-of-deauville.739.html |date=19 March 2012 }}</ref> [[Lower Normandy]] || Guinea, Niger, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and Tunisia accepted their invitations for the first time. Also, the [[Arab League|League of Arab States]] made its debut to the meeting.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/evaluations/2011deauville/kirton-prospects-110526.html |title=Prospects for the 2011 G8 Deauville Summit |work=[[G8 Information Centre]] |first=John| last=Kirton| date=26 May 2011| accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref>|| \n|\n|-\n| [[38th G8 summit|38th]] || 18\u201319 May 2012 || {{Country|United States}} || [[Barack Obama]] || [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] (cancelled)<br /> [[Camp David]], [[Maryland]] (re-located)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/whatsnew/2012location-change.html |title=2012 G8 Summit Relocation |publisher=G8.utoronto.ca |accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref> || The summit was originally planned for Chicago, along with the [[2012 Chicago Summit|NATO summit]], but it was announced officially on 5 March 2012, that the G8 summit will be held at the more private location of Camp David and at one day earlier than previously scheduled.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/03/05/g8-summit-moved-to-camp-david/| title=White House Moves G8 Summit From Chicago To Camp David| work=[[WBBM-TV|CBS Chicago]]| date=5 March 2012| accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> Also, this is the second G8 summit, in which one of the leaders, Vladimir Putin, declined to participate. This G8 summit concentrated on the core leaders only; no non-G8 leaders or international organizations were invited.|| \n|\n|-\n| [[39th G8 summit|39th]] || 17\u201318 June 2013 || {{Country|United Kingdom}}  || [[David Cameron]] || [[Lough Erne]], [[County Fermanagh]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-20408441 |title=BBC News \u2013 Lough Erne resort in Fermanagh to host G8 summit |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=20 November 2012 |accessdate=26 March 2013|work=BBC News }}</ref> || As in 2012, only the core members of the G8 attended this meeting. The four main topics that were discussed here were trade, government transparency, tackling tax evasion, and the ongoing Syrian crisis.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22957599| title=As it happened: G8 summit| work=[[BBC News]]| accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>|| \n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/topical-events/g8-2013|title=UK Presidency of G8 2013|publisher=United Kingdom. gov.uk|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[40th G7 summit|40th]]|| 4\u20135 June 2014 || {{Country|European Union}} || [[Herman Van Rompuy]] <br> [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]] || [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] (re-located from [[Sochi]], [[Russia]]) || G7 summit as an alternative meeting without Russia in 2014 due to association with [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Crimean crisis]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/russia-out-in-the-cold-after-suspension-from-the-g8-1-3345503| title=Russia out in the cold after suspension from the G8| work=The Scotsman| date=18 March 2014| accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref> The 2014 G8 summit in Sochi was cancelled and re-located to Brussels, Belgium without Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303949704579458753312382992?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303949704579458753312382992.html| title=G-7 Agrees to Exclude Russia, Increase Sanctions/World Powers to Meet in Brussels in June Without Russia| work=The Wall Street Journal| date=25 March 2014}}</ref> Emergency meeting in March 2014 in The Hague.|| \n|\n|-\n| [[41st G7 summit|41st]] || 7\u20138 June 2015 || {{Country|Germany}} || [[Angela Merkel]] || [[Schloss Elmau]], [[Bavaria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/germany-to-hold-2015-g8-summit-at-alpine-spa/2014/01/23/66783558-842a-11e3-a273-6ffd9cf9f4ba_story.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140123171618/http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/germany-to-hold-2015-g8-summit-at-alpine-spa/2014/01/23/66783558-842a-11e3-a273-6ffd9cf9f4ba_story.html|url-status=dead|title=Germany to hold 2015 G8 summit at Alpine spa |date=23 January 2014|archivedate=23 January 2014|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> || Summit dedicated to focus on the global economy as well as on key issues regarding foreign, security and development policy.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.g7germany.de/Webs/G7/EN/G7-Gipfel_en/Agenda_en/agenda_node.html|title=German G7 presidency \u2013 Key topics for the summit announced| date=19 November 2014}}</ref> The [[Global Apollo Programme]] was also on the agenda.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carrington|first1=Damian|title=Global Apollo programme seeks to make clean energy cheaper than coal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/jun/02/apollo-programme-for-clean-energy-needed-to-tackle-climate-change|accessdate=2 June 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|issue=2 June 2015|publisher=[[Guardian News Media]]}}</ref>||<small>[http://www.g7germany.de/]</small>\n|\n|-\n| [[42nd G7 summit|42nd]] || 26\u201327 May 2016<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prepsure.com/news/japan-announced-to-host-g7-summit-in-2016-in-shima/| title=Japan announced to host G7 summit in 2016 in Shima| work=prepsure.com| date=23 June 2015| accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/japan-announces-dates-for-g7-summit-in-2016-774332| title=Japan Announces Dates for G7 Summit in 2016| work=NDTV| date=23 June 2015| accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref> || {{Country|Japan}} || [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] || [[Shima, Mie|Shima]], [[Mie Prefecture]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150605/k10010104641000.html |title=\u6765\u5e74\u306e\u30b5\u30df\u30c3\u30c8 \u4e09\u91cd\u770c\u5fd7\u6469\u5e02\u3067\u958b\u50ac\u3078 (Next Year's Summit To Be Held in Shima City, Mie Prefecture) |language=Japanese |date=5 June 2015 |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605093012/http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150605/k10010104641000.html |archivedate=5 June 2015 |df= }}</ref> || The G7 leaders aim to address challenges affecting the growth of the [[world economy]], like slowdowns in [[emerging markets]] and drops in [[price of oil]]. The G7 also issued a warning to the United Kingdom that \"a [[Brexit|UK exit from the EU]] would reverse the trend towards greater global trade and investment, and the jobs they create and is a further serious risk to growth\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|title=Brexit would pose 'serious risk' to global growth, say G7 leaders|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/27/brexit-would-pose-a-serious-risk-to-global-growth-say-g7-leaders|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Guardian|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> Commitment to an EU\u2013Japan Free Trade Agreement.||<small>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160329131940/http://www.g7ise-shimasummit.go.jp/]</small>\n|\n|-\n| [[43rd G7 summit|43rd]] || 26\u201327 May 2017<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rainews.it/dl/rainews/articoli/Renzi-il-G7-del-2017-vorremmo-farlo-in-Sicilia-e-una-scelta-di-politica-culturale-Il-presidente-del-Consiglio-al-G7-in-Giappone-1147181c-342e-40b5-8774-2a197e087cc4.html| title=Renzi announces to host G7 summit in 2017 in Taormina| work=RaiNews24| date=26 May 2016| accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> || {{Country|Italy}} || [[Paolo Gentiloni]] || [[Taormina]], [[Sicily]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blogtaormina.it/2016/04/01/g7-taormina-ufficiale-renzi-chiama-boston-sindaco-giardina-vertice-si-fara-nella-perla/221255|title=G7 a Taormina, \u00e8 ufficiale. Renzi chiama da Boston il sindaco Giardina: \"Il vertice si far\u00e0 nella Perla\"|last=Redazione|date=1 April 2016}}</ref> || G7 leaders emphasized common endeavours: to end the Syrian crisis, to fulfill the UN mission in Libya and reducing the presence of ISIS, ISIL and Da'esh in Syria and Iraq. North Korea was urged to comply with UN resolutions, Russian responsibility was stressed for Ukrainian conflict. Supporting economic activity and ensuring price stability was demanded while inequalities in trade and gender were called to be challenged. It was agreed to help countries in creating conditions that address the drivers of migration: ending hunger, increasing competitiveness and advancing global health security.<ref>{{cite web|title=G7 Taormina Leaders' Communiqu\u00e9|url=http://www.g7italy.it/sites/default/files/documents/G7%20Taormina%20Leaders%27%20Communique_27052017_0.pdf|publisher=G7 Italy 2017|date=27 May 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref>||<small>[http://www.g7italy.it/en]</small>\n|\n|-\n| [[44th G7 summit|44th]] || 8\u20139 June 2018 || {{Country|Canada}}<ref name=\"gcnews\">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2017/05/27/canada-host-2018-g7-summit-charlevoix-quebec|title=Canada to host 2018 G7 Summit in Charlevoix, Quebec|date=27 May 2017|accessdate=27 May 2017|website=pm.gc.ca|publisher=[[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Prime Minister of Canada]]}}</ref> || [[Justin Trudeau]] || [[La Malbaie]], [[Qu\u00e9bec]]|| It took place at the Manoir Richelieu. Prime Minister Trudeau announced five themes for Canada's G7 presidency which began in January 2018. Climate, along with commerce trades, was one of the main themes. \u201c''Working together on climate change, oceans and clean energy''\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.resconrec.2018.02.014|title = A call for Canada to move toward zero plastic waste by reducing and recycling single-use plastics| journal=Resources, Conservation and Recycling| volume=133| pages=99\u2013100|year = 2018|last1 = Walker|first1 = Tony R.| last2=Xanthos| first2=Dirk}}</ref> The G7 members' final statement contains 28 points. US President [[Donald Trump]] did not agree to the economic section of the final statement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2018/06/09/sommet-du-g7-vers-un-communique-final-de-compromis_5312283_3210.html|title=Sommet du G7 : Trump retire son soutien au communiqu\u00e9 commun sur le commerce|newspaper=Le Monde.fr|date=9 June 2018}}</ref> The G7 members also announced to recall sanctions and to be ready to take further restrictive measures against Russian Federation for the failure of Minsk Agreement's complete implementation.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-g7-summit-communique-text/the-charlevoix-g7-summit-communique-idUSKCN1J5107|title=The Charlevoix G7 Summit Communique|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|newspaper=Reuters|date=9 June 2018}}</ref>|| \n|\n|-\n| [[45th G7 summit|45th]] || 24\u201326 August 2019 || {{Country|France}}<ref name=\"presidency rotation 2015-2020\">{{cite news|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_MEMO-14-392_en.htm| title=G7 Summit in Brussels, 4\u20135 June 2014: Background note and facts about the EU's role and action| date=3 June 2014 |accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref> || [[Emmanuel Macron]] || [[Biarritz]], [[Nouvelle-Aquitaine]] || It was agreed at the summit that the World Trade Organization, \"with regard to intellectual property protection, to settle disputes more swiftly and to eliminate unfair trade practices\", \"to simplify regulatory barriers and modernize international taxation within the framework of the OECD\", \"to ensure that Iran never acquires nuclear weapons and to foster peace and stability in the region.\", \"to support a truce in Libya that will lead to a long-term ceasefire\" and addressed the Russian military intervention in Ukraine and the 2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests.<ref name=\"scmp\">{{cite news |title=US President Donald Trump says he believes China sincerely seeks a trade deal |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3024439/us-president-donald-trump-says-he-believes-china-sincerely |work=South China Morning Post|date=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"xinhua\">{{cite news |title=News Analysis: G7 summit declaration cannot conceal deep U.S.-EU rift |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/27/c_138340579.htm |publisher=xinhuanet |date=27 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"lh\">{{cite news |title=Biarritz G7 summit non-binding declaration on Libya calls for truce, political solution and conference |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2019/08/27/biarritz-g7-summit-non-binding-declaration-on-libya-calls-for-truce-political-solution-and-conference/ |work=Libya Herald|date=27 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rthk\">{{cite news |title=G7 leaders back HK autonomy, urge calm |url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1476988-20190827.htm |publisher=rthk.hk |date=27 August 2019}}</ref> ||<small>[https://www.elysee.fr/en/g7]</small>\n|\n|-\n| [[46th G7 summit|46th]] || 10\u201312 June 2020 || {{Country|United States}} (original host)<ref name=\"presidency rotation 2015-2020\"/><br>{{flagicon|}} None ||[[Donald Trump]] (original host figure)|| [[Camp David]], [[Maryland]] (cancelled)<br/>Worldwide videoconference (replaced) || This meeting was originally scheduled to be held in [[Camp David]], [[Maryland]], but that meeting was officially cancelled on March 19, 2020 due to the concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide coronavirus pandemic]] and was replaced by a global videoconference.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/g7-summit-coronavirus-9c91ec94-ab3f-4714-b418-04ee1eafd658.html|title=White House cancels in-person G7 summit at Camp David due to coronavirus|publisher= Media|author=Perano, Ursula|author2=Treene, Alayna|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> || \n|\n|-\n| [[47th G7 summit|47th]] || TBD, 2021 || {{Country|United Kingdom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g7italy.it/cose-g7|title=Come funziona il G7? |website=www.g7italy.it}}</ref> || [[Boris Johnson]] || TBD || || \n|\n|}\n\n===Current leaders===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Member\n!colspan=\"2\"| Representative(s)\n!colspan=\"2\"| Minister of Finance\n! Central Bank Governor\n|-\n| '''[[Canada]]'''\n| [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n| [[Bill Morneau]]\n| [[Stephen Poloz]]\n|-\n| '''[[France]]'''\n| [[President of France|President]]\n| [[Emmanuel Macron]]\n| [[Minister of Economy (France)|Minister of the Economy]]\n| [[Bruno Le Maire]]\n| [[Fran\u00e7ois Villeroy de Galhau]]\n|-\n| '''[[Germany]]'''\n| [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]]\n| [[Angela Merkel]]\n| [[Federal Ministry of Finance (Germany)|Minister of Finance]]\n| [[Olaf Scholz]]\n| [[Jens Weidmann]]\n|-\n| '''[[Italy]]'''\n| [[Prime Minister of Italy|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Giuseppe Conte]]\n| [[List of Italian Ministers of Economy and Finance|Minister of Economy<br />and Finance]]\n|[[Roberto Gualtieri]]\n| [[Ignazio Visco]]\n|-\n| '''[[Japan]]'''\n| [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Shinz\u014d Abe]]\n| [[Minister of Finance (Japan)|Minister of Finance]]\n| [[Tar\u014d As\u014d]]\n| [[Haruhiko Kuroda]]\n|-\n| '''[[United Kingdom]]'''\n| [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Boris Johnson]]\n| [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n| [[Rishi Sunak]]\n| [[Andrew Bailey (banker)]]\n|-\n| '''[[United States]]'''\n| [[President of the United States|President]]\n| [[Donald Trump]]\n| [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]]\n| [[Steven Mnuchin]]\n| [[Jerome Powell]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''[[European Union]]'''\n| [[President of the European Council|Council President]]<ref name=\"EU rep\">[http://euobserver.com/9/29713 \"Van Rompuy and Barroso to both represent EU at G20\"]. EUobserver.com. 19 March 2010. Retrieved 