enter;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[Japan]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1,522,400\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |4,602,367\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |4,767,157\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |36,222\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |37,519\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.909\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 127,061,000\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{N}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1,189,400\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |2,950,039\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |2,569,218\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |45,729\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |39,826\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.922\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 64,511,000\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[United States]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 3,944,000\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |17,348,075\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |17,348,075\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |54,370\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |54,370\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.924\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 318,523,000\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[European Union]]}}\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 4,485,000\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 18,527,116\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 18,640,411\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 36,645\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 36,869\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.899\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 505,570,700\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{n/a}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{n/a}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Emerging and Developing/Advanced<ref>23 out of 28 EU countries are classified as advanced. 5 out of 28 EU countries are classified by the IMF as Emerging and Developing Europe</ref>\n|}\n\nThe G7 is composed of the seven [[National wealth|wealthiest]] advanced countries. The [[China|People's Republic of China]], according to its data, would be the second-largest with 16.4% of the world net wealth,<ref name=\"GWD2018\"/> but is excluded because the IMF and other main global institutions do not consider China an advanced country and because of its relatively low net wealth per adult and HDI.<ref>{{cite web | title=Global Wealth Databook | date=2017 | publisher=[[Credit Suisse]]. credit-suisse.com | url=http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF | access-date=9 June 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF | archive-date=22 November 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> As of 2017 [[Cr\u00e9dit Suisse]] reports the G7 (without the [[European Union]]) represents above 62% of the global [[Net worth|net wealth]].<ref name=\"credit-suisse1\">{{cite web |title=Global Wealth Databook |date=2017 |publisher=[[Credit Suisse]]. credit-suisse.com |at=Table 2-4, \"Wealth Estimates by Country (mid-2017)\u201d, p.&nbsp;101\u2013104. See values of \"Share of Wealth, %\u201d for G7 countries: Canada, 2.6; France, 4.6; Germany, 4.9; Italy, 3.9; Japan, 8.4; United Kingdom, 5.0; and United States, 33.4 (total: 62.8%) |url=http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |access-date=8 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |archive-date=22 November 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Including the EU the G7 represents over 70% of the global net wealth.<ref>[http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF Cr\u00e9dit Suisse] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |date=22 November 2017 }} publication 2.</ref>\n\n===Member facts===\n* 7 of the 7 top-ranked [[advanced economies]] with the current largest GDP and with the highest [[national wealth]] (United States, Japan, Germany, UK, France, Italy, Canada).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2001rank.html| title=CIA World Fact Country Rankings}}</ref>\n* 7 of the 15 top-ranked countries with the highest net wealth per capita (United States, France, Japan, United Kingdom, Italy, Canada, Germany).\n* 7 of 10 top-ranked [[List of countries by exports|leading export countries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2078rank.html|title = exports| publisher= cia factbook}}</ref>\n* 5 of 10 top-ranked countries with the largest [[Gold reserve#Officially reported gold holdings|gold reserves]] (United States, Germany, Italy, France, Japan).\n* 7 of 10 top-ranked economies (by [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|nominal GDP]]), according to latest (2016 data) International Monetary Fund's statistics.\n* 3 countries with a [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|nominal GDP per capita]] above US$40,000 (United States, Canada, Germany).\n* 4 countries with a [[sovereign wealth fund]], administered by either a national or a state/provincial government (United States, France, Canada, Italy).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.swfinstitute.org/fund-rankings/| title=Sovereign Wealth Fund Rankings| work=SWF Institute| accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 7 of 30 top-ranked nations with large amounts of [[List of countries by foreign-exchange reserves|foreign-exchange reserves]] in their [[central bank]]s.\n* 3 out of 9 [[List of states with nuclear weapons|countries having nuclear weapons]] (France, UK, United States),<ref>{{cite news| url=https://fas.org/programs/ssp/nukes/nuclearweapons/nukestatus.html| title=Status of Nuclear Forces|publisher=[[Federation of American Scientists]]| date=26 March 2012| accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-17511816| title=Which countries have nuclear weapons?|publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2012| accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> plus 2 countries that have [[Nuclear sharing|nuclear weapon sharing programs]] (Germany, Italy).<ref name=\"RUSI-2010\">{{Citation|url=http://www.rusi.org/publications/occasionalpapers/ref:O4B991ABDC4148/|title=NATO's Tactical Nuclear Dilemma|author1=Malcolm Chalmers  |author2=Simon Lunn |lastauthoramp=yes |date=March 2010|publisher=[[Royal United Services Institute]]|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,618550,00.html |title=Foreign Minister Wants US Nukes out of Germany |work=Der Spiegel |date=10 April 2009 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n* all 5 of the members of the [[NATO Quint]] (U.S., U.K., France, Germany, Italy) and Canada is also member of [[Five Eyes]] intelligence gathering body with U.S. and U.K.\n* 6 of the 9 largest [[Nuclear power by country#Nuclear power output in megawatts|nuclear energy producers]] (United States, France, Japan, Germany, Canada, UK), although Germany announced in 2011 that it will close all of its nuclear power plants by 2022.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13592208| title=Germany: Nuclear power plants to close by 2022|publisher=BBC| date=30 May 2011| accessdate=12 August 2011}}</ref> Following the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]], Japan shut down all of its nuclear reactors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17967202| title=Tomari shutdown leaves Japan without nuclear power|publisher=BBC News| date=5 May 2012| accessdate=5 May 2012}}</ref> However, Japan restarted several nuclear reactors, with the refueling of other reactors underway.\n* 7 of the 10 top donors to the [[United Nations funding|UN budget]] for the 2016 annual fiscal year.\n* 5 countries with an [[Human Development Index#2019 Human Development Index (2019 report)|HDI index for 2018 of 0.9 and higher]] (United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada, Japan).\n* 2 countries with the [[List of countries by credit rating|highest credit rating]] from [[Standard & Poor's]], [[Fitch Ratings|Fitch]], and [[Moody's Investors Service|Moody's]] at the same time (Canada and Germany).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/10/16/countries-perfect-credit/2995017/ |title=11 countries with perfect credit |work=USA Today|date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n* 3 countries are [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarchies]] (United Kingdom, Canada, Japan), 2 are [[presidential republic]]s (France, United States) and 2 are [[parliamentary republic]]s (Germany and Italy).\n\n==Special invitations==\nFrench President [[Emmanuel Macron]], the host of the G7 summit held in [[Biarritz]] in August 2019, has also invited non-member countries. The invited guest nations include [[Australia]], [[Chile]], [[Egypt]], [[India]], [[Iran]], [[Rwanda]], [[Senegal]], [[South Africa]], and [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=India Invited by France to Be Part of G7 Meet. Here's All You Need to Know About 45th Annual Summit |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/india-invited-by-france-to-be-part-of-g7-meet-heres-all-you-need-to-know-about-45th-annual-summit-2279705.html |website=News18 |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===2014 suspension and subsequent exclusion of Russia===\n{{further|40th G7 summit}}\nIn March 2014 Russia was suspended by G7 members from the political forum G8 following the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]]. After the suspension, on January 2017 the Russian Federation decided permanently to leave the G8. It was confirmed in June 2018.<ref name=\"CNN.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/24/politics/obama-europe-trip/index.html |title=U.S., other powers kick Russia out of G8 |publisher=CNN.com |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russia Is Ousted From Group of 8 by U.S. and Allies|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/25/world/europe/obama-russia-crimea.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 March 2014|access-date=21 December 2015|issn=0362-4331|first=Alison|last=Smale|first2=Michael D.|last2=Shear}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/03/24/there-is-no-g8-russia-suspended-from-exclusive-club-until-it-changes-course-group-of-seven-nations-says/|title=Russia suspended from G8 over annexation of Crimea, Group of Seven nations says |work=National Post |date=24 March 2014|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"russia-suspension\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/russia-g8-kremlin-crimea-ukraine-vladimir-putin-g7-g20-a7525836.html|title=Russia just quit the G8 for good}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/russia-brushes-off-possibility-of-g-8-return|title=Russia brushes off possibility of G-8 return|last=hermesauto|date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 protests===\n{{further|41st G7 summit}}\nAbout 7,500 protesters led by the group 'Stop-G7' demonstrated during the summit. About 300 of those managed to reach the 3&nbsp;m high and 7&nbsp;km long security fence surrounding the summit location despite Germany's immense efforts to prevent it and despite its remote location \u2013 the luxury hotel [[Schloss Elmau]] at the foot of the Wetterstein mountains (altitude of {{convert|1008|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} above sea level). The protesters questioned the legitimacy of the G7 to make decisions that could affect the whole world. Authorities had banned demonstrations in the closer area of the summit location and 20,000 policemen were on duty in Southern Bavaria to keep activists and protesters from interfering with the summit.<ref name=Spiegel07June>{{cite news|title=Der Spiegel: Proteste um Schloss Elmau \u2013 Demonstranten wandern bis zum G7-Zaun.|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/g7-gipfel-protestzug-erreicht-zaun-um-schloss-elmau-a-1037560.html|accessdate=11 June 2015|newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=7 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=Bild03June>{{cite news|title=Bild: 7 Kilometer lang, 3 Meter hoch, auf ganzer L\u00e4nge beleuchtet.|url=http://www.bild.de/regional/muenchen/g7-gipfel/mit-hohem-sicherheitsaufgebot-41201204.bild.html|accessdate=11 June 2015|newspaper=[[Bild]]|date=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Trump conflict over tariffs and Russia===\n{{further|44th G7 summit|Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)}}\nThe [[44th G7 summit|2018 meeting in Charlevoix, Canada]], was marred by fractious negotiations concerning tariffs and Donald Trump's position that Russia should be reinstated to the G7. The Trump administration had just imposed steel and aluminum tariffs on many countries, including European countries that are fellow members of the G7, and Canada, the host country for the 2018 meeting. Trump expressed dismay at Canadian Prime Minister Trudeau for holding a press conference in which Canada restated its position on tariffs (a public criticism of Trump's economic policy), and directed his representatives at the meeting to not sign the economic section of the joint communiqu\u00e9 that is typically issued at the conclusion of the meeting. \nGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel described Trump's behavior as a \"depressing withdrawal,\" while French President Emmanuel Macron invited him \"to be serious.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tg24.sky.it/mondo/2018/06/10/g7-canada-trump.html|title=G7, Trump non-accetta il documento finale. Merkel: \"Ritiro deprimente\" \u2013 Sky TG24|language=it}}</ref> In the final statement signed by all members except the US, G7 announced its intention to recall sanctions and to be ready to take further restrictive measures within the next months against the Russian Federation for its failure to completely implement the [[Minsk Agreement]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nTrump repeated calls for Russia to be re-admitted to the group in the 2019 meeting in [[Biarritz]], saying it should be included in discussions relating to Iran, Syria, and North Korea. Outgoing Italian Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] supported Trump's proposal, [[Shinzo Abe]] of Japan was neutral, and the rest of the G7 pushed back against the suggestion, after which the atmosphere allegedly became \"tense\".\n\n===2019 Amazon rainforest fires and Brazil ===\n{{further|45th G7 summit|2019 Brazil wildfires}}\nU.S. President [[Donald Trump]]'s reiteration of Russia's readmission to the group (see above), instigation of a [[trade war]] with China, increased tensions in Iran, Trump's alleged reticence to attend the conference and a number of international crises made the 2019 G7 meeting in [[Biarritz]], [[France]] the most divided since the inception its founding. Following Trump's previous rescinding of his signature to a joint communiqu\u00e9 agreed in 2018 due to an alleged slight from Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] (see above), French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] agreed that the group would not issue a joint communiqu\u00e9 at the Biarritz conference.<ref name=\"Borger\">{{cite news |last1=Borger |first1=Julian |title=G7: Trump's demands for Russia's readmission cause row in Biarritz |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/25/g7-trumps-demands-for-russias-readmission-causes-row-in-biarritz |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe G7 nations pledged {{USD|20 million}} to help Brazil and other countries in South America to fight the wildfires. This money was welcomed, although many critics saw the measure as being too little, too late.<ref name=\"HenaoSouza\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/efe8b06f1b6b47fd8937938c6333d441|title=Brazil's Bolsonaro causes global outrage over Amazon fires|last1=Henao|first1=Res|date=26 August 2019|work=AP News|accessdate=26 August 2019|last2=Souza|first2=Marcelo De}}</ref> Macron threatened to block a major trade deal between European Union and Brazil ([[Mercosur]]) that would benefit the very agricultural interests accused of driving deforestation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mercosur trade deal gives EU leeway to pressure Brazil on Amazon fires: Maas |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-politics-amazon-germany/mercosur-trade-deal-gives-eu-leeway-to-pressure-brazil-on-amazon-fires-maas-idUSKCN1VG0LJ |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Reuters |date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Big Four (Western Europe)]]\n* [[NATO Quint]]\n* [[Group of Eight]]\n* [[Group of Ten (economics)]]\n* [[G10 currencies]]\n* [[G20]]\n* [[Group of Thirty]]\n* [[Developed country]]\n* [[List of country groupings]]\n* [[List of multilateral free-trade agreements]]\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Group of Seven}}\n{{wikinews|Economic policy makers conclude Washington meetings}}\n* [http://www.g8.utoronto.ca G7/8 Information Centre \u2013 University of Toronto]\n\n{{Group of 7}}\n{{G7 summits}}\n{{International power}}\n{{Western culture}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Group of Seven| ]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental organizations]]\n[[Category:International economic organizations]]\n[[Category:Economic country classifications]]\n[[Category:20th-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:21st-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1975]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{About|the group of seven major advanced nations}}\n{{redirect|G7}}\n{| class=\"wikitable infobox\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|-\n! align=center |Group of Seven and the [[European Union]]\n|-\n|[[File:Group of Seven (G7) Countries.svg|center|315x345px]] {{center|1=The G7-nations (blue) and the European Union (teal) in the world}}\n----\n'''{{flagu|Canada}}'''\n: [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]]\n'''{{flagu|France}}''' \n: [[President of France|President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]]\n'''{{flagu|Germany}}'''\n: [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] ([[List of G7 leaders|Senior G7 Leader]])\n'''{{flagu|Italy}}'''\n: [[Prime Minister of Italy|Prime Minister]] [[Giuseppe Conte]]\n'''{{flagu|Japan}}'''\n: [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] [[Shinzo Abe]]\n'''{{flagu|United Kingdom}}'''\n: [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]]\n'''{{flagu|United States}}''' (2020 host)\n: [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]]\n'''{{flagu|European Union}}'''\n: [[President of the European Council|Council President]] [[Charles Michel]]\n: [[President of the European Commission|Commission President]] [[Ursula von der Leyen]]\n|}\n\nThe '''Group of Seven''' ('''G7''') is an international [[International organization|intergovernmental economic organization]] consisting of the seven largest [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]]- [[Developed country#IMF advanced economies|advanced economies]] in the world: [[Canada]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Japan]], the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2017/02/weodata/weoselco.aspx?g=119&sg=All+countries+%2f+Advanced+economies+%2f+Major+advanced+economies+(G7) |title=World Economic Outlook Database |date=October 2017 |at=Major Advanced Economies (G7) |publisher=International Monetary Fund. imf.org}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, the seven countries involved represent 58% of the [[List of countries by total wealth|global net wealth]] ($317&nbsp;trillion)<ref name=\"GWD2018\">[http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=777FDF0E-E060-F608-52DAF97E062CC35B Research Institute \u2013 Global Wealth Databook 2018]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and more than 46% of the global [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) based on [[Nominal GDP|nominal values]], and more than 32% of the global GDP based on [[purchasing power parity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2018/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=34&pr.y=14&sy=2016&ey=2023&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=156,158,132,112,134,111,136&s=NGDPD,PPPGDP&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org}}</ref> The [[European Union]] is an invitee to G7.\n\nThe annual G7 Summit includes the 7 heads-of-government from these 7 countries.\n\n==History==\n{{Cleanup rewrite|2=section|date=August 2019}}[[File:G7 flags, Toronto.jpg|thumb|left|Flags of G7 members as seen on [[University Avenue (Toronto)|University Avenue in Toronto]]]]\n[[File:G7 in het Catshuis.jpg|thumb|left|G7 leaders during the 2014 emergency meeting about the Russian annexation of Crimea, hosted by the Netherlands]]\nThe concept of a forum for the world's major industrialized countries emerged before the [[1973 oil crisis]]. On Sunday, 25 March 1973, the [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|U.S. Secretary of the Treasury]], [[George Shultz]], convened an informal gathering of [[finance ministers]] from West Germany [[Helmut Schmidt]], France [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]], and the United Kingdom [[Anthony Barber]] before an upcoming meeting in Washington, D.C. When running the idea past President [[Richard M. Nixon|Nixon]], he noted that he would be out of town and offered use of [[White House|the White House]]. The meeting was subsequently held in the [[Library (White House)|library]] on the ground floor.<ref name=\"Schultz\">Shultz, George P. (1993). ''Turmoil and Triumph: My Years as Secretary of State''. p. 148. {{ISBN|0-684-19325-6}}.</ref> Taking their name from the setting, this original group of four became known as the \"Library Group\".<ref>Bayne, Nicholas; Putnam, Robert D. (2000). ''Hanging in There''. Ashgate Pub Ltd. 230 pages. {{ISBN|075461185X}}. p.&nbsp;20.</ref> In mid-1973, at the World Bank-IMF meetings, Shultz proposed the addition of Japan to the original four nations, who agreed.<ref name=\"Schultz\"/> The informal gathering of senior financial officials from the United States, the United Kingdom, [[West Germany]], Japan, and France became known as the \"Group of Five\".<ref>Farnsworth, Clyde H. (8 May 1977). \"A Secret Society of Finance Ministers,\" ''New York Times''.</ref>\n\nThen, in 1974, [[Georges Pompidou|President Pompidou]] of France died and his immediate successor refused to run in the special election, making two changes of [[head of state]] in France in one year. Chancellor Brandt of West Germany was forced to resign in a scandal, and his successor lasted only nine days making two changes in West Germany as well. In addition, then-President of the United States [[Richard Nixon]] and Japanese Prime Minister [[Kakuei Tanaka]] were forced to resign in disgrace. [[Queen Elizabeth II]] was forced to broker a deal to form a government after a [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|hung election]], which was so unstable that [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|another election the same year]] had to take place, and finally, the traditionally unstable government of the 1st Italian Republic changed [[List of Prime Ministers of Italy|Prime Ministers]] yet again. The new American President [[Gerald Ford]], asked some other new heads of state/government to hold a retreat the following year to get to know one another.\n\nIn [[1st G6 summit|1975, a summit]] hosted by France brought together representatives of six governments: France, West Germany, [[Italy]], [[Japan]], the United Kingdom, and the United States. Schmidt and Giscard d'Estaing were heads of government in their respective countries, and since they both spoke fluent English, it occurred to them that they, and British Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]] and U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]] could get together in an informal retreat and discuss election results and the issues of the day. In late spring, d'Estaing of France invited the [[heads of government]] from West Germany, Italy, Japan, the United Kingdom, and the United States to a summit in [[Ch\u00e2teau de Rambouillet]];<ref name=evian>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8.fr/evian/english/navigation/the_g8/questions_about_the_g8.html#question1|title=Evian summit \u2013 Questions about the G8|publisher=Minist\u00e8re des Affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res, Paris|access-date=18 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420120547/http://www.g8.fr/evian/english/navigation/the_g8/questions_about_the_g8.html#question1|archive-date=20 April 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the annual meeting of the six leaders was organized under a rotating presidency, forming the Group of Six (G6). In 1976, with Wilson out as prime minister of Britain, Schmidt and [[Gerald Ford]] felt an English speaker with more experience was needed, so [[Pierre Trudeau]], the Prime Minister of Canada, the next largest advanced economy after the first six, was invited to join the group<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/g8-the-most-exclusive-club-in-the-world-feature/ The Canadian Encyclopedia \u2013 Canada and the G8] ''G8: The Most Exclusive Club in the World'', Thomas S. Axworthy, ''The Canadian Encyclopedia'', Historica Foundation of Canada, Toronto, Undated. Retrieved 23 July 2015.</ref> and the group became the Group of Seven ([[G7]]).<ref name=evian/> Since first invited by the United Kingdom in 1977, the [[European Union]] has been represented by the [[president of the European Commission]] and the leader of the country that holds the [[presidency of the Council of the European Union]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deljpn.ec.europa.eu/union/showpage_en_union.Harry.g8.php |title=EU and the G8 |accessdate=17 July 2006 |publisher=European Union |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226041143/http://www.deljpn.ec.europa.eu/union/showpage_en_union.Harry.g8.php |archivedate=26 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> the [[President of the European Council|Council President]] now also regularly attends.\n\nUntil the 1985 [[Plaza Accord]] no one outside a tight official circle knew when the seven finance ministers met or what they agreed upon. The summit was announced the day before and a communiqu\u00e9 was issued afterwards.<ref>{{cite book|author=Schaefer, Robert K|chapter=Dollar Devaluations|title=Understanding Globalization: The Social Consequences of Political, Economic, and Environmental Change|year=2005|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield|page=346}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[20th G7 summit|1994's G7 summit in Naples]], Russian officials held separate meetings with leaders of the G7 after the group's summits. This informal arrangement was dubbed the Political 8 (P8) \u2013 or, colloquially, the G7+1. At the invitation of [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] [[Tony Blair]] and President of the United States [[Bill Clinton]],<ref>[http://www.theglobalist.com/storyid.aspx?StoryId=5151 \"Russia&nbsp;\u2013 Odd Man Out in the G-8\", Mark Medish, ''The Globalist'', 02-24-2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305052221/http://www.theglobalist.com/storyid.aspx?StoryId=5151 |date=5 March 2008 }}. Accessed: 7 December 2008</ref> Russian President [[Boris Yeltsin]] was invited first as a guest observer, later as a full participant. After the 1997 meeting Russia was formally invited to the next meeting and formally joined the group in 1998, resulting in a new governmental political forum, the [[Group of Eight]] or G8.<ref name=evian/> The Russian Federation, in fact, had and has limited net [[national wealth]] and financial weight compared to the other members of the G8. Russia also has never been a major advanced economy according to the IMF.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2017/02/weodata/weoselgr.aspx|title=Select Country or Country Groups|website=www.imf.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=AD6F2B43-B17B-345E-E20A1A254A3E24A5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921085716/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=AD6F2B43-B17B-345E-E20A1A254A3E24A5 |archive-date=21 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, the Russian Federation was ejected from the G8 political forum in March 2014 following the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russian annexation of Crimea]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/25/world/europe/obama-russia-crimea.html|title=Russia Is Ousted From Group of 8 by U.S. and Allies|last=Smale|first=Alison|date=24 March 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 October 2017|last2=Shear|first2=Michael D.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Early function ==\nThis organization was founded to facilitate shared macroeconomic initiatives by its members in response to the collapse of the exchange rate 1971, during the time of the [[Nixon shock]], the [[1970s energy crisis]] and the ensuing recession.<ref name=Bayne>{{Citation|publisher = Routledge|isbn = 9780415164863|ol = 7484858M|chapter = International economic organizations : more policy making less autonomy|title = Autonomous Policymaking By International Organizations (Routledge/Ecpr Studies in European Political Science, 5)| last  = Bayne| first = Nicholas| editor1-last = Reinalda| editor1-first = Bob| editor2-last = Verbeek| editor2-first = Bertjan|date = 7 December 1998|oclc = 70763323|id = 0415164869}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n{{Location map+ |Europe |width=360 |float=right|caption=Host venues of G7 summits in Europe|places=\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=48.643868|long=1.829079|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[1st G6 summit|1st]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=51.507351|long=-0.127758|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[3rd G7 summit|3rd]], [[10th G7 summit|10th]], [[17th G7 summit|17th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=50.737430|long=7.098207|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[4th G7 summit|4th]], [[11th G7 summit|11th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=45.440847|long=12.315515|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[6th G7 summit|6th]], [[13th G7 summit|13th]]</div>|position=bottom|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=48.804865|long=2.120355|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[8th G7 summit|8th]]</div>|position=top|mark=Arrows 12x12 s.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=48.856614|long=2.352222|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[15th G7 summit|15th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=48.135125|long=11.581981|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[18th G7 summit|18th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=40.882994|long=14.286579|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[20th G7 summit|20th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=45.764043|long=4.835659|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[22nd G7 summit|22nd]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=52.486243|long=-1.890401|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[24th G8 summit|24th]]</div>|position=top|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=50.937531|long=6.960279|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[25th G8 summit|25th]]</div>|position=top|mark=Arrows 12x12 s.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=44.405650|long=8.946256|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[27th G8 summit|27th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=46.401488|long=6.590949|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[29th G8 summit|29th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=56.262051|long=-3.725752|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[31st G8 summit|31st]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=59.853611|long=30.059722|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[32nd G8 summit|32nd]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=54.140810|long=11.840055|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[33rd G8 summit|33rd]]</div>|position=bottom|mark=Arrows 12x12 n.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=42.349848|long=13.399509|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[35th G8 summit|35th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=49.353976|long=0.075122|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[37th G8 summit|37th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=54.479063|long=-7.795287|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[39th G8 summit|39th]]</div>|position=bottom|mark=Arrows 12x12 n.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=50.850340|long=4.351710|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[40th G7 summit|40th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=47.459711|long=11.180518|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[41st G7 summit|41st]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=37.852222|long=15.291944|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[43rd G7 summit|43rd]]'</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Europe  |lat=43.4817|long=-1.55611111111|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[45th G7 summit|45th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n}}\n\nSince 1975, the group meets annually on summit site to discuss economic policies; since 1987, the G7 Finance Ministers have met at least semi-annually, up to four times a year at stand-alone meetings.<ref name= meet>{{cite web|title=G7/8 Ministerial Meetings and Documents|url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/meetings.html|work=G8 Information Centre|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=14 March 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the G7 launched an initiative for the 42 [[heavily indebted poor countries]] (HIPC).<ref>{{cite web|title=Debt Relief Under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative;Perspectives on the Current Framework and Options for Change|url=http://www.imf.org/external/np/hipc/options/|author=International Money Fund|publisher=IMF.org|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the G7 provided $300 million to the effort to build the containment of the reactor meltdown at Chernobyl.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5255663/chernobyl-disaster-book-anniversary/|title=The True Cost of the Chernobyl Disaster Has Been Greater Than It Seems|date=26 April 2018|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the G7 decided to get more directly involved in \"managing the international monetary system\" through the [[Financial Stability Forum]], formed earlier in 1999 and the G-20, established following the summit, to \"promote dialogue between major industrial and emerging market countries\".<ref name=Van>{{cite web|last=Van Houtven|first=Leo|title=Rethinking IMF Governance |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/fandd/2004/09/pdf/vanhoutv.pdf|work=Finance & Development|publisher=International Money Fund|accessdate=25 March 2014|page=18|date=September 2004}}</ref> The G7 also announced their plan to cancel 90% of bilateral, and multilateral debt for the HIPC, totaling $100 billion. In 2005 the G7 announced debt reductions of \"up to 100%\" to be negotiated on a \"case by case\" basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/4238045.stm|title=G7 backs Africa debt relief plan|date=5 February 2005|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the G7 met twice in Washington, D.C. to discuss the global [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Bo Nielsen|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aj_btjkBGNes&refer=home|title=G7 Statement Fails to Convince Major Traders to Change Outlook. |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=14 April 2008}}</ref> and in February 2009 in Rome.<ref>{{cite web|author=Simon Kennedy|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601068&sid=ar19H3Xe0d7o&refer=economy|title=G7 Against the Wall \u2013 Weighs Loan-Guarantee Plan (Update1)|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=10 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090214/ap_on_re_eu/eu_italy_g7|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216193905/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090214/ap_on_re_eu/eu_italy_g7|url-status=dead|title=Yahoo.com|archivedate=16 February 2009}}</ref> The group of finance ministers pledged to take \"all necessary steps\" to stem the crisis.<ref name=\"O'Grady\">{{cite news|last1=O'Grady|first1=Sean|title=G7 pledges action to save banks|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/g7-pledges-action-to-save-banks-957870.html|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=The Independent|date=11 October 2008}}</ref>{{location map+ |North America |float=right|width=230 |caption=Host venues of G7 summits in North America|places=\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=18.458835|long=-66.267668|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[2nd G7 summit|2nd]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=45.651949|long=-74.940872|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[7th G7 summit|7th]]</div>|position=top|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=37.270702|long=-76.707457|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[9th G7 summit|9th]]</div>|position=bottom|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=43.653226|long=-79.383184|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[14th G7 summit|14th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=29.760427|long=-95.369803|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[16th G7 summit|16th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=44.648862|long=-63.575320|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[21st G7 summit|21st]]</div>|position=top|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=39.739236|long=-104.990251|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[23rd G8 summit|23rd]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=51.075562|long=-115.130786|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[28th G8 summit|28th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=31.201728|long=-81.331690|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[30th G8 summit|30th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=45.326932|long=-79.216754|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[36th G8 summit|36th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=39.647537|long=-77.465895|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[38th G8 summit|38th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |North America  |lat=47.654|long=-70.15268|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[44th G7 summit|44th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n}}\n\nOn 2 March 2014, the G7 condemned the \"Russian Federation's violation of the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Ukraine.\"<ref name=toro>{{cite web|url=http://www.g8.utoronto.ca/summit/2014sochi/ukraine_140302.html|title=Statement by G7 Nations|work=G8 Info Ctr|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=10 March 2014|date=2 March 2014}}</ref> The G7 stated \"that the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) remains the institution best prepared to help Ukraine address its immediate economic challenges through policy advice and financing, conditioned on needed reforms\", and that the G7 was \"committed to mobilize rapid technical assistance to support Ukraine in addressing its macroeconomic, regulatory and anti-corruption challenges.\"<ref name=toro /> On 24 March 2014, the G7 convened an emergency meeting in response to the Russian Federation's [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation]] of [[Crimea]] at the official residence of the [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands]], the [[Catshuis]] in [[The Hague]]. This location was chosen because all G7 leaders were already present to attend the [[2014 Nuclear Security Summit]] hosted by the Netherlands. This was the first G7 meeting neither taking place in a member nation nor having the host leader participating in the meeting.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/g7-leaders-descend-on-the-netherlands-for-ukraine-crisis-talks-1.2583287|title=G7 leaders descend on the Netherlands for Ukraine crisis talks|newspaper=CBC news|publisher=Thomson Reuters|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> On 4 June 2014 leaders at the G7 summit in Brussels, condemned Moscow for its \"continuing violation\" of Ukraine's sovereignty, in their joint statement and stated they were prepared to impose further sanctions on Russia.<ref name=\"bbc201406\">{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27707518 | title = G7 leaders warn Russia of fresh sanctions over Ukraine | author=BBC|publisher=BBC|date = 5 June 2014}}</ref> This meeting was the first since Russia was expelled from the G8 following its annexation of Crimea in March.<ref name=\"bbc201406\" />\n\n{{location map+ |Japan |width=230 |float=right|caption=Host venues of G7 summits in Japan|places=\n{{location map~ |Japan |lat=35.689487|long=139.691706|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[5th G7 summit|5th]], [[12th G7 summit|12th]], [[19th G7 summit|19th]]</div>|position=left|mark=Arrows 12x12 e.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Japan|lat=26.591546|long=127.977316|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[26th G8 summit|26th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Japan|lat=42.551269|long=140.764098|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[34th G8 summit|34th]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n{{location map~ |Japan|lat=34.328159|long=136.829691|label= <div style=\"font-size:80%;\">[[42nd G7 summit|42nd]]</div>|position=right|mark=Arrows 12x12 w.svg}}\n}}\n\nThe annual G7 leaders' summit is attended by the heads of government.<ref name=\"feldman1\">{{cite journal|last=Feldman|first=Adam|url=https://www.forbes.com/opinions/2008/07/05/problems-unity-progress-oped-cx_af_summit08_0707feldman.html|title=What's Wrong with the G-8|journal=Forbes|location=New York|date=7 July 2008}}</ref> The member country holding the G7 presidency is responsible for organizing and hosting the year's summit. The serial annual summits can be parsed chronologically in arguably distinct ways, including as the sequence of host countries for the summits has recurred over time and series.<ref>Hajnal, Peter I. (1999). {{Google books|Bi5JO7FFk7UC|''The G8 System and the G20: Evolution, Role and Documentation,'' p. 30.|page=30}}</ref> Generally every country hosts the summit once every 7 years.<ref>[http://www.g7italy.it/cose-g7 G7 Italy 2017], official website.</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==List of summits==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!#\n! style=\"width:15%\" | Date !!style=\"width:15%\"| Host!!style=\"width:15%\"| Host figure !!style=\"width:15%\"| Location held !! Notes!! Website\n!References\n|-\n| [[1st G6 summit|1st]] || 15\u201317 November 1975 || {{Country|France}} || [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]] || [[Ch\u00e2teau de Rambouillet]], [[\u00cele-de-France|District of the Paris Region]] || G6 Summit|| \n|\n|-\n| [[2nd G7 summit|2nd]] || 27\u201328 June 1976 || {{Country|United States}} || [[Gerald R. Ford]] || [[Dorado, Puerto Rico]]<ref name=\"shabecoff\">Shabecoff, Philip. [https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/29/archives/goslow-policies-urged-by-leaders-in-economic-talks-closing.html?sq=+presidentn+Ford++Puerto+Rico+&scp=7&st=p \"Go-Slow Policies Urged by Leaders in Economic Talks; Closing Statement Calls for Sustained Growth Coupled With Curbs on Inflation; Ford's Aims Realized; 7 Heads of Government Also Agree to Consider a New Body to Assist Italy Co-Slow Economic Policies Urged by 7 Leaders,\"] ''The New York Times.'' 29 June 1976; [http://aboutusa.japan.usembassy.gov/e/jusa-usj-chronology.html Chronology, June 1976.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715203839/http://aboutusa.japan.usembassy.gov/e/jusa-usj-chronology.html |date=15 July 2010 }}</ref> ||Also called \"Rambouillet II\". Canada joined the group, forming the G7<ref name=\"shabecoff\" />|| \n|\n|-\n| [[3rd G7 summit|3rd]] || 7\u20138 May 1977 || {{Country|United Kingdom}} || [[James Callaghan]] || [[London]], [[England]] || The [[President of the European Commission]] was invited to [[European Union and the G8|join the annual G7 summits]]|| \n|\n|-\n| [[4th G7 summit|4th]] || 16\u201317 July 1978 || {{Country|West Germany}} || [[Helmut Schmidt]] ||[[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] || || \n|\n|-\n| [[5th G7 summit|5th]] || 28\u201329 June 1979 || {{Country|Japan}} || [[Masayoshi \u014chira]] || [[Tokyo]] || || \n|\n|-\n| [[6th G7 summit|6th]] || 22\u201323 June 1980 || {{Country|Italy}} ||[[Francesco Cossiga]] || [[Venice]], [[Veneto]] ||Prime Minister \u014chira died in office on 12 June; Foreign Minister Sabur\u014d \u014ckita led the delegation that represented Japan.|| \n|\n|-\n| [[7th G7 summit|7th]] || 20\u201321 July 1981 || {{Country|Canada}} || [[Pierre E. Trudeau]] || [[Montebello, Quebec|Montebello]], [[Qu\u00e9bec]] || || \n|\n|-\n| [[8th G7 summit|8th]] || 4\u20136 June 1982 || {{Country|France}