e=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[Japan]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1,522,400\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |4,602,367\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |4,767,157\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |36,222\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |37,519\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.909\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 127,061,000\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{N}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 1,189,400\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |2,950,039\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |2,569,218\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |45,729\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |39,826\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.922\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 64,511,000\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| [[United States]]\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 3,944,000\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |17,348,075\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |17,348,075\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |54,370\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" |54,370\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.924\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 318,523,000\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Advanced\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[European Union]]}}\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 4,485,000\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 18,527,116\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 18,640,411\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 36,645\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 36,869\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 0.899\n| style=\"text-align: right;\" | 505,570,700\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{n/a}}\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:#98fb98;\"| {{Y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{n/a}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Emerging and Developing/Advanced<ref>23 out of 28 EU countries are classified as advanced. 5 out of 28 EU countries are classified by the IMF as Emerging and Developing Europe</ref>\n|}\n\nThe G7 is composed of the seven [[National wealth|wealthiest]] advanced countries. The [[China|People's Republic of China]], according to its data, would be the second-largest with 16.4% of the world net wealth,<ref name=\"GWD2018\"/> but is excluded because the IMF and other main global institutions do not consider China an advanced country and because of its relatively low net wealth per adult and HDI.<ref>{{cite web | title=Global Wealth Databook | date=2017 | publisher=[[Credit Suisse]]. credit-suisse.com | url=http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF | access-date=9 June 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF | archive-date=22 November 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> As of 2017 [[Cr\u00e9dit Suisse]] reports the G7 (without the [[European Union]]) represents above 62% of the global [[Net worth|net wealth]].<ref name=\"credit-suisse1\">{{cite web |title=Global Wealth Databook |date=2017 |publisher=[[Credit Suisse]]. credit-suisse.com |at=Table 2-4, \"Wealth Estimates by Country (mid-2017)\u201d, p.&nbsp;101\u2013104. See values of \"Share of Wealth, %\u201d for G7 countries: Canada, 2.6; France, 4.6; Germany, 4.9; Italy, 3.9; Japan, 8.4; United Kingdom, 5.0; and United States, 33.4 (total: 62.8%) |url=http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |access-date=8 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |archive-date=22 November 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Including the EU the G7 represents over 70% of the global net wealth.<ref>[http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF Cr\u00e9dit Suisse] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122191907/http://publications.credit-suisse.com/tasks/render/file/index.cfm?fileid=A8BD95FB-A213-1EE7-59CC7F2F001A11AF |date=22 November 2017 }} publication 2.</ref>\n\n===Member facts===\n* 7 of the 7 top-ranked [[advanced economies]] with the current largest GDP and with the highest [[national wealth]] (United States, Japan, Germany, UK, France, Italy, Canada).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2001rank.html| title=CIA World Fact Country Rankings}}</ref>\n* 7 of the 15 top-ranked countries with the highest net wealth per capita (United States, France, Japan, United Kingdom, Italy, Canada, Germany).\n* 7 of 10 top-ranked [[List of countries by exports|leading export countries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2078rank.html|title = exports| publisher= cia factbook}}</ref>\n* 5 of 10 top-ranked countries with the largest [[Gold reserve#Officially reported gold holdings|gold reserves]] (United States, Germany, Italy, France, Japan).\n* 7 of 10 top-ranked economies (by [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|nominal GDP]]), according to latest (2016 data) International Monetary Fund's statistics.\n* 3 countries with a [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|nominal GDP per capita]] above US$40,000 (United States, Canada, Germany).\n* 4 countries with a [[sovereign wealth fund]], administered by either a national or a state/provincial government (United States, France, Canada, Italy).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.swfinstitute.org/fund-rankings/| title=Sovereign Wealth Fund Rankings| work=SWF Institute| accessdate=16 February 2012}}</ref>\n* 7 of 30 top-ranked nations with large amounts of [[List of countries by foreign-exchange reserves|foreign-exchange reserves]] in their [[central bank]]s.\n* 3 out of 9 [[List of states with nuclear weapons|countries having nuclear weapons]] (France, UK, United States),<ref>{{cite news| url=https://fas.org/programs/ssp/nukes/nuclearweapons/nukestatus.html| title=Status of Nuclear Forces|publisher=[[Federation of American Scientists]]| date=26 March 2012| accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-17511816| title=Which countries have nuclear weapons?|publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2012| accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref> plus 2 countries that have [[Nuclear sharing|nuclear weapon sharing programs]] (Germany, Italy).<ref name=\"RUSI-2010\">{{Citation|url=http://www.rusi.org/publications/occasionalpapers/ref:O4B991ABDC4148/|title=NATO's Tactical Nuclear Dilemma|author1=Malcolm Chalmers  |author2=Simon Lunn |lastauthoramp=yes |date=March 2010|publisher=[[Royal United Services Institute]]|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,618550,00.html |title=Foreign Minister Wants US Nukes out of Germany |work=Der Spiegel |date=10 April 2009 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n* all 5 of the members of the [[NATO Quint]] (U.S., U.K., France, Germany, Italy) and Canada is also member of [[Five Eyes]] intelligence gathering body with U.S. and U.K.\n* 6 of the 9 largest [[Nuclear power by country#Nuclear power output in megawatts|nuclear energy producers]] (United States, France, Japan, Germany, Canada, UK), although Germany announced in 2011 that it will close all of its nuclear power plants by 2022.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13592208| title=Germany: Nuclear power plants to close by 2022|publisher=BBC| date=30 May 2011| accessdate=12 August 2011}}</ref> Following the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]], Japan shut down all of its nuclear reactors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17967202| title=Tomari shutdown leaves Japan without nuclear power|publisher=BBC News| date=5 May 2012| accessdate=5 May 2012}}</ref> However, Japan restarted several nuclear reactors, with the refueling of other reactors underway.\n* 7 of the 10 top donors to the [[United Nations funding|UN budget]] for the 2016 annual fiscal year.\n* 5 countries with an [[Human Development Index#2019 Human Development Index (2019 report)|HDI index for 2018 of 0.9 and higher]] (United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada, Japan).\n* 2 countries with the [[List of countries by credit rating|highest credit rating]] from [[Standard & Poor's]], [[Fitch Ratings|Fitch]], and [[Moody's Investors Service|Moody's]] at the same time (Canada and Germany).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/10/16/countries-perfect-credit/2995017/ |title=11 countries with perfect credit |work=USA Today|date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n* 3 countries are [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarchies]] (United Kingdom, Canada, Japan), 2 are [[presidential republic]]s (France, United States) and 2 are [[parliamentary republic]]s (Germany and Italy).\n\n==Special invitations==\nFrench President [[Emmanuel Macron]], the host of the G7 summit held in [[Biarritz]] in August 2019, has also invited non-member countries. The invited guest nations include [[Australia]], [[Chile]], [[Egypt]], [[India]], [[Iran]], [[Rwanda]], [[Senegal]], [[South Africa]], and [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=India Invited by France to Be Part of G7 Meet. Here's All You Need to Know About 45th Annual Summit |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/india-invited-by-france-to-be-part-of-g7-meet-heres-all-you-need-to-know-about-45th-annual-summit-2279705.html |website=News18 |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===2014 suspension and subsequent exclusion of Russia===\n{{further|40th G7 summit}}\nIn March 2014 Russia was suspended by G7 members from the political forum G8 following the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]]. After the suspension, on January 2017 the Russian Federation decided permanently to leave the G8. It was confirmed in June 2018.<ref name=\"CNN.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/24/politics/obama-europe-trip/index.html |title=U.S., other powers kick Russia out of G8 |publisher=CNN.com |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russia Is Ousted From Group of 8 by U.S. and Allies|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/25/world/europe/obama-russia-crimea.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 March 2014|access-date=21 December 2015|issn=0362-4331|first=Alison|last=Smale|first2=Michael D.|last2=Shear}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/03/24/there-is-no-g8-russia-suspended-from-exclusive-club-until-it-changes-course-group-of-seven-nations-says/|title=Russia suspended from G8 over annexation of Crimea, Group of Seven nations says |work=National Post |date=24 March 2014|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"russia-suspension\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/russia-g8-kremlin-crimea-ukraine-vladimir-putin-g7-g20-a7525836.html|title=Russia just quit the G8 for good}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/russia-brushes-off-possibility-of-g-8-return|title=Russia brushes off possibility of G-8 return|last=hermesauto|date=9 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 protests===\n{{further|41st G7 summit}}\nAbout 7,500 protesters led by the group 'Stop-G7' demonstrated during the summit. About 300 of those managed to reach the 3&nbsp;m high and 7&nbsp;km long security fence surrounding the summit location despite Germany's immense efforts to prevent it and despite its remote location \u2013 the luxury hotel [[Schloss Elmau]] at the foot of the Wetterstein mountains (altitude of {{convert|1008|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} above sea level). The protesters questioned the legitimacy of the G7 to make decisions that could affect the whole world. Authorities had banned demonstrations in the closer area of the summit location and 20,000 policemen were on duty in Southern Bavaria to keep activists and protesters from interfering with the summit.<ref name=Spiegel07June>{{cite news|title=Der Spiegel: Proteste um Schloss Elmau \u2013 Demonstranten wandern bis zum G7-Zaun.|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/g7-gipfel-protestzug-erreicht-zaun-um-schloss-elmau-a-1037560.html|accessdate=11 June 2015|newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=7 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=Bild03June>{{cite news|title=Bild: 7 Kilometer lang, 3 Meter hoch, auf ganzer L\u00e4nge beleuchtet.|url=http://www.bild.de/regional/muenchen/g7-gipfel/mit-hohem-sicherheitsaufgebot-41201204.bild.html|accessdate=11 June 2015|newspaper=[[Bild]]|date=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Trump conflict over tariffs and Russia===\n{{further|44th G7 summit|Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)}}\nThe [[44th G7 summit|2018 meeting in Charlevoix, Canada]], was marred by fractious negotiations concerning tariffs and Donald Trump's position that Russia should be reinstated to the G7. The Trump administration had just imposed steel and aluminum tariffs on many countries, including European countries that are fellow members of the G7, and Canada, the host country for the 2018 meeting. Trump expressed dismay at Canadian Prime Minister Trudeau for holding a press conference in which Canada restated its position on tariffs (a public criticism of Trump's economic policy), and directed his representatives at the meeting to not sign the economic section of the joint communiqu\u00e9 that is typically issued at the conclusion of the meeting. \nGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel described Trump's behavior as a \"depressing withdrawal,\" while French President Emmanuel Macron invited him \"to be serious.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tg24.sky.it/mondo/2018/06/10/g7-canada-trump.html|title=G7, Trump non-accetta il documento finale. Merkel: \"Ritiro deprimente\" \u2013 Sky TG24|language=it}}</ref> In the final statement signed by all members except the US, G7 announced its intention to recall sanctions and to be ready to take further restrictive measures within the next months against the Russian Federation for its failure to completely implement the [[Minsk Agreement]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nTrump repeated calls for Russia to be re-admitted to the group in the 2019 meeting in [[Biarritz]], saying it should be included in discussions relating to Iran, Syria, and North Korea. Outgoing Italian Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] supported Trump's proposal, [[Shinzo Abe]] of Japan was neutral, and the rest of the G7 pushed back against the suggestion, after which the atmosphere allegedly became \"tense\".\n\n===2019 Amazon rainforest fires and Brazil ===\n{{further|45th G7 summit|2019 Brazil wildfires}}\nU.S. President [[Donald Trump]]'s reiteration of Russia's readmission to the group (see above), instigation of a [[trade war]] with China, increased tensions in Iran, Trump's alleged reticence to attend the conference and a number of international crises made the 2019 G7 meeting in [[Biarritz]], [[France]] the most divided since the inception its founding. Following Trump's previous rescinding of his signature to a joint communiqu\u00e9 agreed in 2018 due to an alleged slight from Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] (see above), French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] agreed that the group would not issue a joint communiqu\u00e9 at the Biarritz conference.<ref name=\"Borger\">{{cite news |last1=Borger |first1=Julian |title=G7: Trump's demands for Russia's readmission cause row in Biarritz |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/25/g7-trumps-demands-for-russias-readmission-causes-row-in-biarritz |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe G7 nations pledged {{USD|20 million}} to help Brazil and other countries in South America to fight the wildfires. This money was welcomed, although many critics saw the measure as being too little, too late.<ref name=\"HenaoSouza\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/efe8b06f1b6b47fd8937938c6333d441|title=Brazil's Bolsonaro causes global outrage over Amazon fires|last1=Henao|first1=Res|date=26 August 2019|work=AP News|accessdate=26 August 2019|last2=Souza|first2=Marcelo De}}</ref> Macron threatened to block a major trade deal between European Union and Brazil ([[Mercosur]]) that would benefit the very agricultural interests accused of driving deforestation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mercosur trade deal gives EU leeway to pressure Brazil on Amazon fires: Maas |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-politics-amazon-germany/mercosur-trade-deal-gives-eu-leeway-to-pressure-brazil-on-amazon-fires-maas-idUSKCN1VG0LJ |accessdate=26 August 2019 |work=Reuters |date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Big Four (Western Europe)]]\n* [[NATO Quint]]\n* [[Group of Eight]]\n* [[Group of Ten (economics)]]\n* [[G10 currencies]]\n* [[G20]]\n* [[Group of Thirty]]\n* [[Developed country]]\n* [[List of country groupings]]\n* [[List of multilateral free-trade agreements]]\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Group of Seven}}\n{{wikinews|Economic policy makers conclude Washington meetings}}\n* [http://www.g8.utoronto.ca G7/8 Information Centre \u2013 University of Toronto]\n\n{{Group of 7}}\n{{G7 summits}}\n{{International power}}\n{{Western culture}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Group of Seven| ]]\n[[Category:Intergovernmental organizations]]\n[[Category:International economic organizations]]\n[[Category:Economic country classifications]]\n[[Category:20th-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:21st-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1975]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:a5aa:8b28:e8ba:2b57:e957:16b1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_of_Seven"}
